</caption>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="195" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="3.[136,1452,1551,1865]" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,478,1551,1577]" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">Distribution and ecology</emphasis>
:—The plant occurs in the Tatroute gorges (Assaka, Tounfite), at elevations of 
<quantity metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.375" metricValueMax="2.8" metricValueMin="1.95" pageId="3" pageNumber="195" unit="m" value="2375.0" valueMax="2800.0" valueMin="1950.0">1950–2800 m</quantity>
a.s.l., between upper-mesomediterranean and lower supramediterranean vegetation 
<typeStatus box="[1096,1159,1588,1614]" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">types</typeStatus>
. Semi-arid bioclimates. In all known populations, the species was found growing on cracks in shady calcareous vertical cliffs.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[136,1452,1551,1865]" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,428,1659,1685]" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">Known distribution</emphasis>
:—The species appears to be endemic to a small area in the Maasker mountains (
<figureCitation box="[1366,1437,1659,1686]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="5.[136,229,2020,2042]" captionTargetBox="[435,1155,1226,1978]" captionTargetId="figure-48@5.[421,1167,1216,1995]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 6. Geographic distribution of Centaurea peltieri (■), Centaurea takredensis (●), Centaurea atlantis (▲), Centaurea gattefossei () and C. oriolii-bolosii ()." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5585484" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5585484/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
), High Atlas. This territory corresponds to the geographical unit “HA-6: 
<collectingRegion box="[942,1034,1695,1721]" country="Morocco" name="Oriental" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">Oriental</collectingRegion>
High Atlas” of 
<bibRefCitation author="Fennane, M." box="[1216,1396,1695,1722]" pageId="3" pageNumber="195" refId="ref2053" refString="Fennane, M. (2016) Elements pour un Livre Rouge de la flore vasculaire du Maroc, fasc. 1. Pteridophyta (version 1, nov. 2016). Tela- Botanica. Licence CC-BY NC ND." type="book" year="2016">Fennane (2016)</bibRefCitation>
. The species has been found on many shady cliffs; the overall population could exceed 200 individuals.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="195" type="conservation">
<paragraph blockId="3.[136,1452,1551,1865]" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,349,1767,1793]" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">Conservation</emphasis>
:—The known populations of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Homrani-Bakali &amp; Susanna" authorityYear="2021" box="[683,796,1767,1794]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Centaurea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="3" pageNumber="195" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="peltieri">
<emphasis box="[683,796,1767,1794]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">C. peltieri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are strictly limited to specific ecological conditions. As we go outside the shady cliffs, we don’t find the plant anymore. However, more surveys should be made to circumscribe the distribution of the species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</subSection>
